<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_PID_mod_Jordan" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>PID-module structure theorems: Jordan canonical forms</title>
    
   <p>
    Amazingly, by treating the case <m>R=F[x]</m>, where <m>F</m> is a field, the PID-module structure theorems gives us some advanced theory about linear transformations for finite-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector spaces essentially for free! Before getting into details, we first make an observation about modules over a general polynomial ring. 
   </p>
   <proposition xml:id="prop_mods_poly_ring">
    <title>Modules over a polynomial ring</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>R</m> be a commutative ring. 
        </p>
                    <p>
                        If <m>M</m> is an <m>R[x]</m>-module, then in particular <m>M</m> is an <m>R</m>-module, and the map <m>\phi_x\colon M\rightarrow M</m> defined as <m>\phi_x(m)=x\cdot m</m> is an <m>R</m>-module endomorphism of <m>M</m>. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Conversely, if <m>M</m> is an <m>R</m>-module and <m>\phi\colon M\rightarrow M</m> is an <m>R</m>-module endomorphism of <m>M</m>, then <m>M</m> can be a given an <m>R[x]</m>-module structure by defining 
                        <md>
                            <mrow>(\sum_{k=0}^na_kx^k) \cdot m \amp = \sum_{k=0}^na_k\phi^k(m) </mrow>
                        </md>.
                    </p>
            <p>
                In other words, an <m>R[x]</m>-module consists of an <m>R</m>-module <m>M</m>, together with a choice of <m>\phi\in \End_R(M)</m> that determines how elements of <m>M</m> are multiplied by <m>x</m>. 
            </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Proof by delegation.
        </p>
    </proof>
   </proposition>
   <p>
    The proposition is the key that will allow us to connect linear transformations of vector spaces to the PID-module structure theory. Firstly, if <m>F</m> is a field, then we know that <m>F[x]</m> is a PID. Now, let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, and let <m>T\colon V\rightarrow V</m> be a linear transformation of <m>V</m>. Using the language of module theorem, <m>V</m> is a finite free <m>F</m>-module, and <m>T\in \End_F(V)</m> is an <m>F</m>-endomorphism of <m>V</m>.  
   </p>
   <p>
    According to our proposition, <m>V</m> inherits an <m>F[x]</m>-module structure from <m>T</m> by defining <m>x^n\cdot v=T^n(v)</m>, and more generally, <m>g(x)\cdot v=g(T)(v)</m>. Since <m>V</m> is finitely generated over <m>F</m>, it is certainly finitely generated over <m>F[x]</m>. We conclude that as an <m>F[x]</m>-module, 
    we have 
    <md>
        <mrow>V \amp \cong (F[x])^n\oplus\bigoplus_{i=1}^m F[x]/(g_i(x))</mrow>
    </md>
    for some polynomials <m>g_i(x)\in F[x]</m>. Next, since <m>V</m> is a finite-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space and <m>F[x]</m> is an infinite-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, we must have <m>n=0</m> and  
    <md>
        <mrow> V \amp \cong \bigoplus_{i=1}^m F[x]/(g_i(x)) </mrow>
    </md>.
    Great, but what does this tell us about the linear transformation <m>T</m>? 
   </p>
<definition xml:id="d_minimal_char_poly">
<title>Minimal and characteristic polynomial</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>F</m> be a field, let <m>V</m> be a finite-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, and let <m>T\colon V\rightarrow V</m> be a linear transformation. 
<ul>
    <li>
        <title>Characteristic polynomial</title>
        <p>
            The <term>characteristic polynomial</term> of <m>T</m> is the polynomial <m>\ch_T(x)</m> defined as 
            <md number="yes">
                <mrow xml:id="eq_char_poly">\ch_T(x) \amp = \det(xI-A) </mrow>
            </md>,
            where <m>A=[T]_B</m> is a(ny) matrix representation of <m>T</m> with respect to a a basis <m>B</m> of <m>V</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            The <term>minimal polynomial</term> of <m>T</m> is the unique monic polynomial <m>m_T(x)\in F[x]</m> of minimal degree satisfying <m>m_T(T)=0_V</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ul>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<remark>
    <title>Minimal and characteristic polynomial</title>
    <p>
        Assume <m>V</m> is a <m>n</m>-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, and let <m>T\in \End_F(V)</m> be a linear transformation. The minimal polynomial is the unique monic generator of 
        <md>
            <mrow>\Ann V \amp =\{g\in F[x]\mid g(T)=0_V\}</mrow>
        </md>.
        By the Cayley-Hamilton theorem (proved in great generality in your homework), we have <m>\ch_T(T)=0_V</m>, and thus <m>m_T(x)\mid \ch_T(x)</m>. 
    </p>
</remark>
<theorem xml:id="th_Jordan_decomp">
<title>Jordan decomposition</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>V</m> be an <m>n</m>-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, and let <m>T\in \End_F(V)</m> be a nonzero linear transformation.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            There exists a unique sequence of nonconstant monic polynomials <m>(a_i(x))_{i=1}^m</m> satisfying <m>a_i(x)\mid a_{i+1}</m> for all <m>1\leq i\leq m-1</m> and 
            <md>
                <mrow xml:id="eg_Jordan_decomp_invariant"> V \amp\cong_{F[x]} \bigoplus_{i=1}^m F[x]/(a_i(x)) </mrow>
            </md> .
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            There exists a unique set of distinct monic irreducible polynomials <m>p_1(x),p_2(x),\dots, p_r(x)</m>, and for each <m>1\leq i\leq r</m> a unique sequence of positive integers 
            <md>
                <mrow>n_{i1} \amp \leq n_{i2}\leq \dots \leq n_{im_{i}} </mrow>
            </md>
            such that 
            <md>
                <mrow xml:id="eq_Jordan_decomp_elem_div" >V \amp \cong_{F[x]} \bigoplus_{\substack{1\leq i\leq r\\ 1\leq j\leq m_{i}}}F[x]/(p_i(x)^{n_{ij}}) </mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
<corollary xml:id="cor_min_char_poly">
    <statement>
        <p>
Let <m>V</m> be an <m>n</m>-dimensional <m>F</m>-vector space, and let <m>T\in \End_F(V)</m> be a nonzero linear transformation. We treat <m>V</m> as an <m>F[x]</m>-module via the action of <m>T</m> on <m>V</m>. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>(a_i(x))_{i=1}^m</m> be the monic invariant factors of <m>V</m>. We have 
            <md>
                <mrow>m_T(x) \amp = a_m(x)</mrow>
                <mrow>\ch_T(x) \amp =\prod_{i=1}^m a_i(x)</mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Let <m>p_1(x),p_2(x),\dots, p_r(x)</m> be the distinct monic irreducible polynomials appearing in the elementary factors decomposition of <m>V</m>, and for each <m>1\leq i\leq r</m>, let <m>(n_{ij})_j</m> be the accompanying unique sequence of integers. We have 
            <md>
                <mrow> m_T(x) \amp = \prod_{i=1}^r p_i(x)^{n_{im_i}} </mrow>
                <mrow>\ch_T(x) \amp = \prod p_{i}(x)^{n_{ij}} </mrow>
            </md>.
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
    </statement>
</corollary>

</section>